}

{
    "analysis": "From the metric aggregates: we inspected 34 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs from the five candidate services within the incident window. Many pairs have only a small number of points that breach global P95 or P5 (typically count_ge_p95_in_window=2 and count_le_p5_in_window=2). Socket KPIs are constant and equal to both P95 and P5 and therefore uninformative. At this stage we cannot yet pick a single root cause because no obvious long consecutive fault window was reported in the compact aggregates. According to the workflow, we must perform fault identification by finding consecutive anomalous runs (to filter out isolated spikes) so we can then use traces and logs to localize the root cause among candidate services.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For all (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs among the five candidates (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice) that had any anomalies in the previous aggregate (count_ge_p95_in_window>0 or count_le_p5_in_window>0), analyze the incident-window series (2024-01-19 22:30:43 to 2024-01-19 23:00:43 UTC) and detect consecutive anomalous runs. Define a high anomaly as value >= global P95 and a low anomaly as value <= global P5, where P95/P5 are computed over the full available series for that pair. For each detected run with run_length >= 2, return one compact row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_type ('high' or 'low'), run_start_utc, run_end_utc, run_length (number of consecutive points), max_value_in_run, min_value_in_run, severity_ratio (for 'high' = max_value_in_run / p95; for 'low' = p5 / min_value_in_run). Limit output to top 50 runs ordered by run_length desc then severity_ratio desc. Keep output compact (one row per run)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric-based preprocessing, threshold calculation, anomaly detection, and preliminary fault identification. Metrics across the five candidate services produced only brief, low-severity anomalous runs (mostly run_length=2 with severity ratios ≈1.00) and many trivial constant 'socket' alerts that equal P95/P5. No sustained, high-severity metric fault was found that clearly pins the root cause. According to the workflow, when multiple service-level candidates exist (or when metrics are inconclusive), we must use traces to localize the downstream faulty service. Therefore the next step is trace analysis: compute global thresholds for trace features per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full trace series, then inspect the incident window (2024-01-19 22:30:43 to 2024-01-19 23:00:43 UTC) for trace anomalies (points >=P95 or <=P5). We should report compact aggregates (counts, earliest anomaly timestamp, severity, min/max in window) only for candidate services and only where anomalies exist, limited to top 20 rows.",
