{
    "analysis": "So far we followed the prescribed workflow: (1) Preprocessing and threshold calculation for metrics across the five candidate services produced global P95/P5 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name). (2) Metric anomaly detection found only short, low-severity runs (mostly length=2, severity ≈1.00) and many trivial constant 'socket' anomalies equal to thresholds — no sustained resource fault. (3) Trace error_rate features are uniformly zero (p95=p5=0) and therefore uninformative for anomaly detection. (4) Log analysis surfaced meaningful deviations in log.row_count for checkoutservice, emailservice, and recommendationservice (a few elevated and reduced samples during the incident window). At this junction metrics and trace error rates are inconclusive; per the rules we should use traces (especially latency/duration traces) to localize the downstream faulty service among the three services with row_count anomalies. We need to check duration-related trace features (e.g., trace.*.duration_mean or duration_p95) for those three services by computing global thresholds (using the full series) and then checking the incident window for sustained/high-severity anomalies (>=P95). This will help identify the most downstream faulty service in traces if any service shows significant duration spikes during the incident window.",
